Let’s get started!

Materials

  • All materials including this slide set are available at:
    • https://github.com/kamataak/WorkshopSMU2020
  • Download all materials.
    • Click on “Code”.
      • If you know how to use Git, clone it!
    • Otherwise, click on “Download ZIP”.
      • The entire folder will be downloaded to your download folder as a compressed ZIP file.
      • Move the ZIP file where you desire.
      • Unzip the folder.

Download R

  • Download R from the R-Project website.
    • http://www.r-project.org
    • Follow the links to go to the download page.
      • Go to “CRAN”
      • Then, choose one of the links, such as one under “0-Cloud”.
    • R is available for Windows, Mac OS, and Linux platforms.

Install R

  • Currently, a stable version is 4.02.
  • Run the downloaded installer to install R, and follow the instructions.
    • You can accept all default specifications.

Download & Install RStudio

  • Download from RStudio website.
    • https://rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/
    • Download the free version.
  • Then, install RStudio by running the downloaded installer.
  • When installation of RStudio is completed, be sure that it opens with R in the console pane.

Part 1: Workflow on RStudio

Recommended Work Management on RStudio

Steps: 1 & 2 Preparation of Project Folder

  • Create a new folder. This is will become a Project Folder.
  • Copy the data file to analyze to this Project Folder.
    • For this demonstration, download a CSV data from: https://bit.ly/3cJcU08
    • For a realistic situation, you will copy a necessary data file into this folder.

Step 3: Open RStudio

  • Open RStudio, just like opening other programs on your computer.
  • It will automatically link to R.

Step 4a: Create a New R Project

  • At this point, the project name says “Project (None)” on the upper right corner.
    • This indicates that no project is open yet on this RStudio window.
  • Click on “Create a Project” button.
    • Click on “Existing Directory”.
    • Then, click on “Browse…” and select the target Project Folder, where the data file was copied.
    • Click on “Create Project”.

  • Now, you will have RStudio open with a new project.
    • Notice the label for the project on the upper right corner has changed.
  • Notice that a new file with .Rproj has been created in the project folder.
    • This is a project file, and will store information about the project.
    • Also, when you resume your work for this project, you will double click this file to open RStudio and the project.

Step 4a: Install Required Packages

  • I have already installed some key packages.
  • Note:
    • R comes with only limited set of base packages.
      • To do something realistic, we almost always need to use other packages.
      • Also, usability of R can be dramatically enhanced by additional packages.
    • In practical use of R in research, one would constantly look for a solution.
      • A solution is likely to require a package to be installed.

  • I have installed:
    • tidyverse
      • A collection of several packages for data manipulations and visualizations.
      • We can use so many functions and features in packages available from this package.

  • I have also installed:
    • sjmisc
      • A package that offers additional data manipulation utilities.
      • Also, it comes with nice functions to generate a frequency table and descriptive statistics.
    • sjlabelled
      • Collection of functions dealing with labelled data, like reading and writing data between R and other statistical software packages like ‘SPSS’, ‘SAS’ or ‘Stata’, and working with labelled data.

Step 4b: Open a New R Notebook

  • Choose an “R Notebook” option from the pull-down menu on the button right under the “File” menu.

  • Then, a new R Notebook file “Untitled1” will be open.
    • The file is populated with a template, which contains some suggested shortcut keys.

  • Erase all contents, except lines 1 - 4.

  • We are ready to go!
  • Let’s name this R Notebook file with a meaningful name.
    • Click on the diskette-shape icon, right below the "Untitle1*" tab.

Note: When your work has not been saved, you see the R Notebook tab in red with asterisk.

  • Type a file name, say “Notebook01”.
  • Then, click on “Save”.

  • Notice two files has been created:
    • Notebook01.Rmd
      • This is the R Notebook file we are working on.
    • Notebook01.nb.html
      • This is an HTML file to output the content and results of the R Notebook file.

  • Let’s take a peek the HTML file.
    • Click the file name of the HTML file.
    • Choose “View in Web Browser”.

  • Quite empty for now…

  • Let’s add & edit some information in the first few lines and save:

Note:

  • The first few lines tagged by three dashes “- - -” is called YAML header.
  • R Notebook updates the HTML file every time we save the Notebook file.

  • Very nice!
  • The next step is to add some R code and comments to the R Notebook file.

Step 5a: Load Required Packages

  • Required packages have been installed.
  • However, required packages need to be loaded every time we start a session.
    • Installing and loading a package are two different things.
  • Let’s write a code to load required packages.

  • Create a new code chunk.
    • Choose R, under the “Insert” button.
      • Alternatively, option + command + I shortcut keys.

  • Code chunk is where we write R code.
  • We can write comments outside of code chunk.

  • Line 8: Add a comment outside of the code chunk.
  • Line 9: Add a specification not to output messages. [Optional]
  • Lines 10-11: Write two new lines of R code to load two packages:
    • tidyverse for reading an CSV format data, as well as for data manipulations.
    • sjmisc for generating a frequency table.

  • To run this code chunk, click on the green arrow on the upper-right corner of the code chunk (gray-shaded area).

Step 5a: Read Data File

  • Place a cursor on line 15, and create another code chunk. Then,

    • Line 14: Add a comment outside of the code chunk.

    • Line 15: Add a specification not to output messages. [Optional]

    • Lines 16-17: Write 2 new lines of R code:

      • To read the data file into a data object Chapman.dat (line 16)
      • To display the data object (line 17)

  • Run this code chunk by clicking on the green arrow on the upper-right corner of the code chunk.

  • Also, the data object will appear in the “Environment” tab in the upper-right pane.

  • As another way to view the data, we can click on the data object name in the “Environment” tab.

  • This is just a data viewer, and we cannot edit the data on the viewer.
    • We can still sort and filter the data to explore the data.

  • By now, we have a nice Notebook to show R codes, comments, and output.
    • This is a nice way to build and manage your work.
      • Write R code and run.
      • See results.
      • Write comments.
  • Recall that we also have an HTML file produced by the Notebook file.
    • Save the Notebook file, and check the HTML file.

Steps 6-8: Do Something with Data

  • Let’s generate a frequency table for the variable CORON2.

    1. Create a new R code chunk.
    2. Select the variable CORON2 by the select function.
      • This function is from dplyr package as part of tidyverse package.
    3. Use frq function to generate a frequency table.
      • This function is from sjmisc package.

  • %>% is called a pipe operator, which is part of tidyverse package.
    • In short, the left-hand side of %>% will be passed to the right-hand side as the first entry of the function.
    • It is extremely useful for executing multiple operations sequentially.

  • Let’s save the Notebook file and check the HTML file.

Step 9: Close Project

  • Be sure to save your Notebook file for the last time.
  • It is highly recommended NOT to save the “workspace”, because you can easily replicate your work by running the saved syntax.

Resuming Existing Work

  • Step 4: Open RStudio by double-clicking a saved R Project file (.Rproj file).
    • The target R script file will be automatically open, if it was open when you closed RStudio last time.
    • Otherwise, go to “Files” tab of RStudio, and click the target R script file name to open.

  • Step 5: Run all code chunks.
    • Run one by one by clicking green arrows.
    • Or select “Run All” from “Run” button.

  • Now you are back to where you were.
    • You can develop additional work.

Let’s Do It 1

  • Replicate what have been demonstrated:
    1. Create a new folder FirstRprojedt, and copy the data file Chapman.csv.
    2. Open RStudio, and create a new project for the newly created folder.
    3. Install tidyverse package, if you have not.
    4. Open a new script file, and write lines to read the Chapman.csv data as Chapman.dat.
    5. Save the R script file by naming it FirstRscript.
    6. Close RStudio.
    7. Re-open RStudio by double-clicking FirstRproject.Rproj.

Let’s Do It 2

  • Learn about how to do some data manipulations.
    1. Create a new folder DataTransformations, and download data files easyCBM.csv and easyCBM.sav.
    2. Also, download an R Notebook Rmd file 02_DataTransformations.Rmd to the folder.
    3. Open RStudio, and create a new project for this newly created folder.
    4. Install sjmisc and sjlabelled packages, if you have not.
    5. Open the R Notebook Rmd file 02_DataTransformations.Rmd.
    6. Study each code chunk and run.

Let’s Do It 3

  • Learn about how to generate some descriptive statistics.
    1. Create a new folder DescriptiveStatistics, and copy a data file easyCBM.sav.
    2. Also, download an R Notebook Rmd file 05_DescriptiveStat1.Rmd to the folder.
    3. Open RStudio, and create a new project for this newly created folder.
    4. Install psych package, if you have not.
    5. Open the R Notebook Rmd file 05_DescriptiveStat1.Rmd.
    6. Study each code chunk and run.
